Analysis of scores on the ngs data

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib import rc
from sklearn.neighbors import KernelDensity
from glob import glob
import re

'''
old_50k contains the ~50K selected activators. This file is >1 year old ("results_score_sorted_nonzeros3_10.csv").
new_1M should contain ~1.8M sequences ("ARG3_O1_O2.tsv", after clustering?). Since the number
of reads per bin are slightly different than in old_50k I map the 50K seqs into the new_1M file and compute Soeding's new score.
'''

old_50k = pd.read_csv('./results_score_sorted_nonzeros6_10.csv', delimiter='\t')
new_1M = pd.read_csv('./ARG3_O1_O2.tsv', delimiter='\t')

# Overcome any difference in the names of trhe indexes
for df in [old_50k, new_1M]:
    df.columns = np.insert(df.columns,1,'sequence')[1:]
    df.set_index('sequence', inplace=True)

# map old_50 sequences into the new_1M
ids = list(old_50k.index)
df = new_1M.loc[ids]

# calculate the "newest_score". I call it the "newest" because is newer than Lukasz's new score.
df['newest_score'] = ( 1.0 / df[['bg','bin1','bin2','bin3','bin4']].sum(axis=1) ) * ( np.sum( np.array([0,1,2,4,8]) * df[['bg','bin1','bin2','bin3','bin4']], axis=1) )

# scatter plot and correlation
x = df.score.fillna(0).values
y = df.newest_score.fillna(0).values

# How do newest and old scores correlate?
plt.scatter(x,y, c='k', s=1, alpha=0.2)
plt.title('r = '+'{:.2f}'.format(np.corrcoef(x,y)[0][1])+' for the 50k activators')
plt.xlabel('Default Lukasz scores', size=14)
plt.ylabel('new Johannes\'s proposed scores', size=14)

Fitting the linear model with all available samples: 18

# library to fit the linear model
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from scipy.stats.mstats import spearmanr

# file containing all data for the 18 mutants
validation_df = pd.read_csv('./activity_measurements-for-18-peptide-seqs.tsv', delimiter='\t')
values_bins = validation_df[['background_number','bin1_number','bin2_number','bin3_number','bin4_number']]


# Normalize the values of the bins per sample  
X = ( 1.0 / values_bins.sum(axis=1) ).reshape(-1,1) * values_bins.values
y = validation_df['GFP fluo'].values

# Find the optimal weights and use them to get the r and Sr
linear_model = LinearRegression().fit(X,y) 
x = np.sum( linear_model.coef_ * X, axis=1)
r = np.sqrt( linear_model.score(X,y) )
Sr = spearmanr(np.sum([0,1,2,4,8] * X, axis=1),y)[0]; SR=r'S$_{r}$'

# plot sequence scores with fitted weights vs GFP fluorescence 
weights = ', '.join(['{:.2f}'.format(i) for i in linear_model.coef_])
plt.scatter(x,y)
plt.xlabel('linear regression scores')
plt.ylabel('GFP fluorescence')
plt.title('r = {:.2f}, {} = {:.2f}\nweights = , '.format(r, SR, Sr) + weights)

To avoid these weird negative numbers I can use a non-negative least-squares fitting

# nnls: "https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.optimize.nnls.html" 
from scipy.optimize import nnls
weights, rnorm = nnls(X,y)
x_positive = np.sum( weights * X, axis=1)
r = np.corrcoef(x_positive, y)[0][1]
weights = ', '.join(['{:.2f}'.format(i) for i in weights])
plt.scatter(x_positive, y)
plt.xlabel('linear regression (W>0) scores')
plt.ylabel('GFP fluorescence')
plt.title('r = {:.2f}\nweights = , '.format(r) + weights)

Still non-sense… backround has too much importance in these models. I keep it 0.

# Same as above but with background weight set to 0
X_true = X[:,1:]

weights_str = ', '.join(['{:.2f}'.format(i) for i in weights])

How are the scores distributed throughout the samples?

# Density plot of scores on the same data
X_50k = old_50k[['background_number','bin1_number','bin2_number','bin3_number','bin4_number']].fillna(0)
X_50k = ( 1 / np.sum(X_50k, axis=1) ).reshape(-1,1) * X_50k

# Extracting or calculating different scores for the 50k set
old_k = old_50k.normalized_enrichment_slope_score
newest_k = np.sum( X_50k * [0,1,2,4,8], axis=1 )
linear_model_true_k = np.sum( weights * X_50k.ix[:,1:], axis=1 )

#To see where the 18 validation mutants fall within the distributions
gfp = validation_df.set_index('sequence')['GFP fluo']
gfp_norm = ( gfp-gfp.min() ) / ( gfp.max()-gfp.min() )
# points contain the score and gfp fluo  
old_k_points = pd.concat([old_k,gfp_norm], axis=1, join='inner').values
newest_k_points = pd.concat([newest_k, gfp_norm],axis=1, join='inner').values
linear_model_true_k_points = pd.concat([linear_model_true_k, gfp_norm], axis=1, join='inner').values

# On the 50k activators
plt.figure()
plt.suptitle('On the 50k activators')
bw = [0.001, 0.4, 50]
for i, j in zip(['old_k', 'newest_k', 'linear_model_true_k'], range(1,5)):
    print i
    vals = vars()[i].values
    # Density estimation
    kde = KernelDensity(bandwidth=bw[j-1]).fit((vals.reshape(-1,1))) 
    scale = np.max(vals)-np.min(vals)
    x_plot = np.linspace(np.min(vals)-scale*0.2, np.max(vals)*1.1, 200)
    prob = np.exp( kde.score_samples(x_plot.reshape(-1,1)) )
    # plot the distribution
    plt.subplot(2,2,j)
    plt.plot(x_plot, prob, lw=2)
    # plot the 18 mutants, their gfp gluorescence adapted to the y-scale
    scale_proba = np.max(prob) - np.min(prob)
    plt.scatter(vars()[i+'_points'][:,0], vars()[i+'_points'][:,1]*scale_proba, s=3)
    # aesthetics
    plt.title(i)
    [plt.xlabel('score') if j>1 else '']; plt.ylabel('freq')
    # To focus on a region where things happen 
    if j==5:
        plt.xlim(-10,1000)

Dots are the 18 mutants with their scores in the x-axis and their relative GFP-fluorescence in the y-axis. Dataset contains ~50k activators.
